	<text id="ruskin_to_mother_july_09_1867_2">
	    
	    <header>
	        <inventNo>1996L00312</inventNo>
	    </header>
	
	    <body>
	        <div type="text">
	            <pb n="1"/>           
	            <opener>
	                <placeName><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs key="Q1025076" type="place">Keswick,</rs>
	                </placeName>
	                <day>Tuesday Evening</day>
	                <date when="1867-07-09"><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs type="date">9th July 1867</rs>
	                </date>
	                <salute>My dearest <rs key="47637407" type="person">Mother</rs></salute><!-- match letter exactly, delete if unnecessary -->
	            </opener>
	            
	            <p id="p1">
	                <s id="s1">I must leave this behind me here, for I shall not catch the post to-morrow at <rs key="Q1017196" type="place">Wigtown</rs>.</s>
	                <s id="s2">It has been a hot, dark, oppressive day, but I took a long walk to the foot of <rs key="Q4925984" type="place">Saddleback</rs> on the old <rs key="Q1025076" type="place">Keswick</rs> and <rs key="Q798906" type="place">Penrith</rs> road.</s>
	                <s id="s3">The descent on the <rs key="Q1025076" type="place">vale of Keswick</rs> by the hill - some mile and a half long, of the old mail road, is supremely beautiful, and people 	were better taking four days to reach the lakes, and so approaching them,<pb n="2"/> than now, coming from <rs key="Q84" type="place">London</rs> in nine hours, and being projected very nearly into the lake out of a tunnel.</s>
	            </p>   
	
	            <p id="p2"> 
	                <s id="s4">I heard of your friend <rs key="miss_wright" type="person">Miss Wright</rs>, the botanist to-day, but alas, not favourably: - she is an old maid, still an excellect botanist, but so grasping and selfish that she will <add hand="#JR">(it is said)</add> tear a plant up by the roots which she does not want herself, for fear anybody else should get it.</s>
	                <s id="s5">However, this is only hearsay.</s>
	                <s id="s6">I will see her myself when I return, and give you my own notion of her.</s>
	            </p>
	
	            <pb n="3"/> 
	
	            <p id="p3"> 
	                <s id="s7">I never yet saw <rs key="Q156533" type="flora">foxgloves</rs>, or wild <rs key="Q34687" type="flora">roses</rs>, so beautiful as they are on all the hillsides and in all the hedges, here.</s>
	                <s id="s8">But mineralogy is at a discount</s>
	                <s id="s9"><rs key="miss_wright" type="person">Wright</rs> in <rs key="Q1544344" type="place">Great Russell Street</rs> had more <rs key="Q23360" type="place">Cumberland</rs> minerals that all the dealers in <rs key="Q1025076" type="place">Keswick</rs>, except show things in windows - some of the masses of <rs key="Q44793182" type="mineral">fluor</rs> and <rs key="Q677" type="mineral">iron</rs> which they keep for furniture are the grandest I ever saw, but merely noticable for size.</s>
	            </p>
	            
	            <p id="p4">
	                <s id="s10">I hope to get to <rs key="Q1017196" type="place">Wigtown</rs> by three to-morrow, and that you will have a letter on Thursday morning.</s>
	            </p>
	
	            <closer>
	                <salute>Ever my dearest <rs key="47637407" type="person">Mother</rs>, Your most affectionate Son,</salute><!-- optional - delete if unnecessary -->
	                <signed><!-- optional - delete if unnecessary -->
	                    <rs key="73859585" type="person">J. Ruskin</rs>
	                </signed>
	             </closer>
	
	        </div>
	    </body>
	</text>      
	
